[Student "S"]
{North is to play 6NT. East leads the \SK.

You have 11 winners; 1 \S, 2 \Hs, 4 \Ds and 4 \Cs. If you can make a trick with the \SJ all will be well. But if not, as long as East holds the \SQ, which is almost a certainty, you will be able to squeeze him in \Ss and \Hs. 

The first thing you should do is to duck the \SK. If East foolishly plays another \S your troubles are over. But he doesn't, he plays the \HQ instead which you win with dummy's \HK.  

Even though East didn't play a second \S your first round duck served a very important purpose - it rectified the count for your squeeze.

Next play off your 4 \D winners, discarding a small \H from your hand. 

You are now zeroing in on East.

Play the \CK, \CJ, then over to your \CQ. 

[showcards N:S7,S4,HA,H3 E:S9,S8,S6,C8 S:SA,SJ,H7,CA W:SQ,ST,HJ,H9]

Here is the layout after the 3 \C plays. Everybody followed suit except East who discarded a \H (unhappily, it seemed). 

When you now play your \CA, discarding a \S from dummy, East is squeezed.

If he discards the \ST, then his \SQ will fall underneath your \SA, establishing your \SJ.

But if he instead throws the \H9, both of dummy's \Hs will become winners.}
[Play "W"]SK

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:752.AT8.A93.AQ82 T8.KQJ963.T4.763 AKQ6.742.KQJ7.K5 J943.5.8652.JT94"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1C 2H X pass 2NT pass 6NT all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "8ae93f3d069591845d429611e04dafba0d671a90bb09a5177ca6ccc8ff3ae0d4"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/squeeze_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 6NT. South leads the \HK.

As usual, you have 11 winners; 3 \Ss, 1 \H, 4 \Ds and 3 \Cs. If \Ss split 3-3 dummy's \S6  will become trick #12. If \Ss don't split though, you will have the chance of a squeeze if the defender with long \Ss also has 4 or more \Cs.

For a squeeze to operate you will need to lose one trick and the time to do that is right now. Let South hold the \HK and win his \H continuation with your \HA. 

North discarded a \D on the second \H.

You might as well find out about the \Ss right now. Play the \S A K Q. 

Too bad, South discards a \H on the third round of \Ss.  

North now holds the the only guard in \Ss.

Play the \DA, then \D K Q. 

North will follow to all three \Ds.  

Now for the squeeze. Play dummy's \DJ and discard your \H10.

If North discards the \SJ you will cash dummy's \S6, then win the last 3 \C tricks. 

So North will no doubt throw a \C instead. In which case you win the last 4 \C tricks.

Squeezes are so very satisfying.}
[Play "W"]HK

